# Copy to .env, then fill in the real (gitignored) values.
# This file is committed as documentation — keep placeholder values only,
# never real secrets.

# ── Drizzle ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Local Postgres used by Drizzle. Start it with:
#   pnpm run db:start
# Then apply the schema with `pnpm run db:push` (or generate/run migrations
# via `pnpm run db:generate` + `pnpm run db:migrate`).
DATABASE_URL="postgres://root:mysecretpassword@localhost:5433/local"

# In a deployed Worker, Postgres access goes through the "HYPERDRIVE" binding
# (see wrangler.jsonc), not DATABASE_URL — see src/lib/server/db/index.ts.
# For local dev this DATABASE_URL is what's actually used, since resolving
# the Hyperdrive binding falls back to it whenever no live Cloudflare
# context is present.

# SvelteKit's own canonical-origin var (also read as better-auth's baseURL
# below) — same convention @sveltejs/adapter-cloudflare / better-auth expect.
ORIGIN="http://localhost:5173"

# ── Better Auth ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Generate with: openssl rand -base64 32
BETTER_AUTH_SECRET=""

# Google OAuth 2.0 Web client — https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials
#   Authorized redirect URI: http://localhost:5173/api/auth/callback/google
#   Authorized JS origin:     http://localhost:5173
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=""
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=""

# ── Logging ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# App logger (src/lib/server/logger.ts) level: debug | info | warn | error
# (default: info)
# LOG_LEVEL=info

# ── Cloudflare Queues (async job processing) ──────────────────────────
# In a deployed Worker (or real `wrangler dev`), sendJob (src/lib/server/queue.ts)
# uses wrangler.jsonc's native HELLO_QUEUE producer binding — no env vars
# needed there. Plain `vite dev` never resolves that binding (same as
# HYPERDRIVE — see src/lib/server/db/index.ts), so it needs the local-only
# bridge below; without it, the "Async Job" demo card's submitHelloJob form
# action throws immediately (by design — see src/lib/server/queue.ts's sendJob).
#
# Local dev, no Cloudflare account needed: point sendJob at this worker's
# local dev address. Deliberately NOT `wrangler dev`'s generic default port
# (8787) — that port is contested with this repo's Next.js sibling
# template's equivalent local queue setup, which can silently steal the port
# (and then silently "succeed" against the wrong project's worker).
# `worker:dev` (see package.json) pins this project's worker to 8797 instead:
QUEUE_LOCAL_PUSH_URL=http://localhost:8797
# Then run `pnpm run worker:dev` (wrangler dev --config wrangler.queue.jsonc
# --port 8797) in a second terminal — it simulates the "hello"/"hello-dlq"
# queues entirely locally via Miniflare and exposes a local-only HTTP
# endpoint (gated by .dev.vars — copy .dev.vars.example to .dev.vars first)
# that stands in for the native queue binding.
